**US to Return Nuclear Capability to B-52 Bombers**
The US is planning to return the ability to carry nuclear weapons to approximately 30 B-52H Stratofortress bombers. This decision is based on a congressional resolution. The planes were previously modified to carry only conventional weapons under an agreement with Russia on arms control. Lawmakers aim to increase the US nuclear arsenal due to Russia's suspension of the treaty and China's rapid expansion of strategic nuclear capabilities. Opponents of the move argue that it will complicate negotiations for a new treaty and make it harder to extend the service life of the B-52 fleet, which was first introduced during the Cold War. The relevant bill in the House of Representatives requires the US Air Force to complete the restoration of the nuclear potential of the bombers by 2029. The B-52 is the oldest bomber in the US fleet, having been in service since the 1960s. It was previously reported that some American B-52s had their nuclear bombs removed. The only nuclear weapon allowed to be carried by these planes is the AGM-86B air-launched cruise missile with a W80-1 warhead.
