**Global Spending on Nuclear Weapons Reaches 91.4 Billion Dollars in 2023**
The global spending on nuclear weapons has reached 91.4 billion dollars in 2023, a 13% increase from the previous year. According to the International Campaign to Abolish Nuclear Weapons (Ican), all nine nuclear-armed states have increased their spending, with the United States leading the way with 51.1 billion dollars. The report highlights that this spending could be used to combat climate change, save endangered species, and improve healthcare and education worldwide. Ican also notes that the last three countries to possess nuclear weapons - Israel, India, and Pakistan - do not provide transparent data. The organization is calling for a global week of action from September 16 to 22 with the slogan 'No money for nuclear weapons!' and is urging people to communicate what they would prefer the money to be spent on. According to Ican, in the last five years, 387 billion dollars have been spent on nuclear weapons, with an annual increase of 34%. The report also reveals that nuclear-armed states have contracts with companies worth at least 387 billion dollars to produce nuclear weapons, with some contracts extending until 2040. These profits incentivize nuclear weapon producers to spend millions of dollars to influence government policy and public opinion through think tanks.
